              <span id="reviewTextContainer1706743873" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8085653926071286441"><i>The Labyrinth of Solitude: Life and Thought in Mexico</i> is Octavio Paz’s project of describing a National Mexican Identity. Of course I immediately had my doubts. Anthropologists / cultural critics are always saying how projects that attempt to grasp any sort of national character are impossible, misguided. Nations are composed of heterogeneous peoples, all of different cultural traditions, historical backgrounds, economic classes… How could we even attempt to find a generalization that fits all o</span>
  <span id="freeText8085653926071286441" style="display:none"><i>The Labyrinth of Solitude: Life and Thought in Mexico</i> is Octavio Paz’s project of describing a National Mexican Identity. Of course I immediately had my doubts. Anthropologists / cultural critics are always saying how projects that attempt to grasp any sort of national character are impossible, misguided. Nations are composed of heterogeneous peoples, all of different cultural traditions, historical backgrounds, economic classes… How could we even attempt to find a generalization that fits all of these people? And even if we did, what good would that do us? Of course I am skeptical of Paz’s assertion that the Mexican (man) never reveals his True Character, is always wearing a mask and is always becoming the “other” of himself (except in times of Great Passion where his bottled emotions burst forth, resulting in Death, Orgasm, or Hangover). Are all Mexicans like this? Probably not. But it’s interesting to think about why Paz, the great decorated Mexican Poet, comes to this conclusion. <br /><br />He spends a lot of time grappling with the problem of creating something that is Truly Mexican. Paz, like many other latin american authors, believes that Mexico’s True Authentic Literature has yet to be written. Everything up until this point has just been copying Europe. We need to break from this tradition, he says, and create something truly new! Authentic! Ourselves! But this is so paradoxical on so many levels (I mean first of all, does there even exist anything that is truly authentic? Without external influence? Let’s just assume that there does):<br /><br /><blockquote>1. How could the Mexican even make something authentic and True when the True Identity of the Mexican (according to Paz) is to hide one’s True Self behind a mask?<br /><br />2. Mexico was colonized by Europeans; modern mexican culture is a mixture of colonial Spaniards, indígenos, and African slaves. So of course there will always be threads of European tradition in whatever art gets made by Mexicans.<br /><br />3. Even if they did create something truly original, truly separate from Europe, it would only be in response to whatever is Truly European. To make something anti-European is to still be influenced by Europe. In other words, do you think the Aztecs ever thought about making art that was Truly Original and Separate from Europe?? (I kind of even think that Art As We Know It is inherently western. Other cultures may have a different concept of What Art Is, practices that may have different functions beside what we consider to be aesthetic functions, or involve different relationships between Artist, Art Object, Viewer, and Context. But that is another discussion!)</blockquote><br />Is the solution, then, to internalize their exotic position? Will the Mexican only ever be able to either A. make art that is just a pale reflection of their colonizers’, or B. violently reject their art and, in doing so, still respond to them?<br /><br />Paz would argue that these paradoxes are what inform the Mexican Character. “Viva Mexico, hijos de la chingada!” he quotes. Paz’s Mexican is born from the violated woman, La Malinche, Hernán Cortés’s mistress, the Mexican Eve. But even though Mexico itself was founded on colonialism, slavery, destruction of whole cultures and their mythologies, languages, knowledges, etc. the culture today is just as much European as it is indígeno, and African. Because so much of their culture comes from Europe, so much of their identity is actually european, how can they differentiate themselves from their oppressors, their violent father Spain, while still acknowledging their roots? Paz gets close to some kind of solution of acceptance on pg. 103:<br /><br /><blockquote>I am not attempting to justify colonial society. In the strictest sense, no society can be justified while one or another form of oppressions subsists in it. I want to understand it as a living and therefore contradictory whole. In the same way, I refuse to regard the cruelty of the human sacrifices of the Aztecs as an isolated expression of cruelty without relation to the rest of that civilization. Their tearing-out of hearts and their monumental pyramids, their sculpture and their ritual cannibalism, their theocracy and their great myths, are all an indissoluble one. To deny this would be as infantile as to deny Gothic art or Provencal poetry in the name of the medieval serfs, or to deny Aeschylus because there were slaves in Athens. History has the cruel reality of a nightmare, and the grandeur of man consists in his making beautiful and lasting works out of the real substance of that nightmare. Or, to put it another way, it consists in transforming the nightmare into vision; in freeing ourselves from the shapeless horror of reality--if only for an instant--by means of creation. </blockquote><br />Later, Paz mentions a couple times how Mexicans should strive to transcend their National Character and make art that is truly Universal. At this point I am thinking, “no no no!!!!!” because so often the word Universal (“Timeless Universal Truths” as my 10th grade English teacher used to repeat) is just code for “Relatable to Any Upper-Class White Dude!” Universal truths, like love! Loss! Death! Is The Great Equalizer! Etc! Basically anything that can be understood outside of any political context. Did Paz think that the goal of Mexican art should transcend the political altogether??<br /><br />Good question! I do think it is true that art/poetry/lit/whatever can never be reduced to JUST a purely symptomatic expression of a historical context. “To reduce poetry to its reflections of historical events and movements would be like reducing the poet's words to their logical or grammatical connotations,” says Paz. Or, furthermore, that the moral imperative of a/p/l/w should always be to express a political message, promoting the Revolution, or whatever. We know from Castro, for example, that only funding art that promotes the Revolution prevents any sort of critical, groundbreaking work outside of that paradigm from being made. Or when we look at the genre of music called Conscious Rap, it’s always just kind of…. Meh! Paz would agree (p. 159):<br /><br /><blockquote>In Europe and the United States, the intellectual has been deprived of power. He lives in exile, so far as the state is concerned, and wields his influence from outside the government, with criticism as his principal mission. In Mexico, the intellectual’s mission is political action. The Mexican intelligentsia has not only served its country, it has also defended it, honestly and effectively. But in so doing, has it not ceased to be an intelligentsia? That is, has it not renounced its proper role as the critical conscience of its people? </blockquote><br />So we see that the goal of a Mexican Art can’t just be expressly political, but it also can’t deny the political situation altogether. So what does Paz mean by Universal, then?? 193:<br /><br /><blockquote>The struggles in the Orient are related in one way or another to our own. Our nationalism, to be more than a mental illness or self-adulation, must search the whole world. We must recognize that our alienation is not unique, that it is shared by a majority of the world’s peoples. </blockquote><br />Okay then. That’s fine. If we’re going to try to be universal, we’ll do it for the other “third world” people around the world, not to capitulate to European interests.<br /><br />All in all, thoughtful writing that I would recommend to anyone interested in Latin American history, culture, and/or literature. And it is really rewarding to read this and his poetry concurrently; I find that a lot of the concepts in The Labyrinth are touched on in his poetry, like how two colliding stars in the night are two solitary Mexicans striving for communion; i.e. True Love as an act of Radical Transgression. Or how the immobile Mexican sun is “the eternity of the poetic instant” and all the different ways that we can even conceive of time at all. So much!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8085653926071286441" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


