<div id="review_114734767" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/114734767" />
    <a title="Will" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4094670-will"><img alt="Will" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1517954363p2/4094670.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/114734767?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Will" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Will" href="/user/show/4094670-will">Will</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer114734767" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11782588783177373524">My infatuation with the Mexican mask culture must somehow mirror that of the Jungian persona; after all, man is amidst, in the words of José Corostiza, a &quot;wilderness of mirrors.&quot; <br/><br/>Paz has created an air of holistic realm, giving psychological, sociological, anthropological, and historical insights and adding the zest of poetry, artistic creation, and the art of love to conclude an interpretation and understanding of Mexican culture so vivid, yet so dark.<br/><br/><u>The Labyrinth of Solitude</u> presents an argum</span>
  <span id="freeText11782588783177373524" style="display:none">My infatuation with the Mexican mask culture must somehow mirror that of the Jungian persona; after all, man is amidst, in the words of José Corostiza, a "wilderness of mirrors." <br /><br />Paz has created an air of holistic realm, giving psychological, sociological, anthropological, and historical insights and adding the zest of poetry, artistic creation, and the art of love to conclude an interpretation and understanding of Mexican culture so vivid, yet so dark.<br /><br /><u>The Labyrinth of Solitude</u> presents an argument ranging in dynamics: from the <i>Pachuco</i> gangs to Mexican isolation, from Spanish conquest and colonization to the Revolution and Zapata, from the elaborate fiestas to the everyday masks of the Mexican, from adolescent creativity to feminist philosophy. <br /><br />The work is dated by such recent history as the Zapatista movement, capitalistic infiltration, and social media, which brings the whole ever more closely in their "search for communion." (Though Paz is referring to love here, is it not our ultimate goal?) To understand the struggle of a culture, in this instance Mexican, and recognize the history of its people can only improve an understanding of the present day. Many of the cultural aspects Paz speaks of will always exist as a part of Mexican life, despite the communal binds of the information age and social media. After all, these are merely tools of our age in which we utilize to offer more of ourselves at the table.<br /><br />After reading Paz's essay, I've realized more than just the dichotomy of everyday living he reasons that humanity has created. We are caught with everything in between our polar contrasts: birth and death, communion and isolation, structure and freedom. Never does he dwell too much with one extreme, unless he ties in other topics for a holistic view. Often times, arguments are caught in the limbo of validity without proper applications ; Paz never loses sight of his topic, even after interweaving so many micro-points as to give further insight.<br /><br />I rate this four-stars only because he does serve as a product of his time and place in history and additional knowledge needs to be acquired to see that a few of his arguments are invalid nowadays.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11782588783177373524" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


