<div id="review_1549177599" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1549177599" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1549177599?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=essays">essays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1549177599" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14600632452012906483">Intense, richly written essays on history and society from a deeply perceptive mind. Now, granted, I don&apos;t know nearly enough about Mexican history to be able to verify or falsify his statements about various Mexican leaders and ideologies, but they&apos;re impressive arguments, and good groundwork for why Mexico remained a semi-colonial state decades after independence. Delving deep into topics ranging from 19th Century debates over positivism, the role of the fiesta in village life, Aztec myth, the</span>
  <span id="freeText14600632452012906483" style="display:none">Intense, richly written essays on history and society from a deeply perceptive mind. Now, granted, I don't know nearly enough about Mexican history to be able to verify or falsify his statements about various Mexican leaders and ideologies, but they're impressive arguments, and good groundwork for why Mexico remained a semi-colonial state decades after independence. Delving deep into topics ranging from 19th Century debates over positivism, the role of the fiesta in village life, Aztec myth, the omnipresence of death in Mexican society, this is in many ways both a harsh rebuke and an open-hearted love letter to Paz's homeland, and contains some of the finest social essays I've ever read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14600632452012906483" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


