  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1653213319" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1653213319" />
    <a title="Samantha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9127414-samantha"><img alt="Samantha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1494767823p2/9127414.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1653213319?book_show_action=true">May 30, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Samantha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Samantha" href="/user/show/9127414-samantha">Samantha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9127414-samantha?shelf=read-in-2016">read-in-2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9127414-samantha?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9127414-samantha?shelf=20th-century-history">20th-century-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1653213319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2458757495870030187">For my own reasons, again, it took me awhile to finish this one. This includes increasingly lengthy and frequent periods of not reading at all, though. I had to finish it if only because it&apos;s really good. It is both poetic and politically far-seeing. It also keeps getting better as it goes along. It pays dividends that way, but by no means do I mean that the original &quot;Labyrinth of Solitude&quot; is &quot;slow&quot; or &quot;hard to get into.&quot; It&apos;s not, though of the constituent parts of this edition it dates itself</span>
  <span id="freeText2458757495870030187" style="display:none">For my own reasons, again, it took me awhile to finish this one. This includes increasingly lengthy and frequent periods of not reading at all, though. I had to finish it if only because it's really good. It is both poetic and politically far-seeing. It also keeps getting better as it goes along. It pays dividends that way, but by no means do I mean that the original "Labyrinth of Solitude" is "slow" or "hard to get into." It's not, though of the constituent parts of this edition it dates itself the most--and I even mean that relatively. The shortest way to put it is that it's a book about the idea of Mexico rather than the situation of Mexico. One can read "The Labyrinth of Solitude" and find it insightful while not really agreeing with it. I almost felt like it bordered on stereotyping the Mexican even though its "stereotyped" Mexican was dramatically more complex and 3-dimensional than what would have commonly existed in the minds of Americans at the time it was published. The revisions and essays that follow, however, put the lie to that first impression. In those, Paz revisits and discusses both his own work and the history and idea of Mexico in a changing context. Part of the joy in the book as a whole is watching Paz turn over the newest iterations of the same problem over and over again in his evidently fertile mind. For him criticism is everything. Looking forever to the past leads to stagnation; looking forever to the future to nihilism. Neither Mexico or the US will find its salvation in religion or charismatic politics, in state art or consumerism. I appreciate that he calls it "criticism," not skepticism, art, or "critical thinking." Criticism encompasses those, of course, but one has the sense that his intended audience is public intellectuals. Reading this so many years on, for me anyway, underscores the diminished role in society that public intellectuals now occupy in the era of the internet and the 24-hour news cycle. We tend to see everything and process almost nothing, to say nothing of the analysis and higher-order evaluation involved in criticism. It's that prescience beyond the surface subject matter that makes this a 5-star book and a touchstone that will likely lead to further reading in a few directions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2458757495870030187" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


