        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer121379391" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4898437382627023270">Octavio Paz mastered the role of the one of the most trenchant essayist of the 20th century. Leaving his coat of poet in the corner his gives reader incredible journey to the sole of Mexican nation, more precisely to the soul of Mexican and thus man and his solitude.<br/>With his tremendous skills he analysis Mexican culture and Mexican nations. Día de los Muertos (The Day of the Dead) is perceived from European view as totally hardly to be taken and understood, however Octavio Paz wrote excellent es</span>
  <span id="freeText4898437382627023270" style="display:none">Octavio Paz mastered the role of the one of the most trenchant essayist of the 20th century. Leaving his coat of poet in the corner his gives reader incredible journey to the sole of Mexican nation, more precisely to the soul of Mexican and thus man and his solitude.<br />With his tremendous skills he analysis Mexican culture and Mexican nations. Día de los Muertos (The Day of the Dead) is perceived from European view as totally hardly to be taken and understood, however Octavio Paz wrote excellent essay which cover this extraordinary perception of a death in Latin America.<br /><br />Furthermore, his essays go even further to the soul of man and his solitude. Giving clear consequences of the Conquest and Spanish Colonialism Paz made the bridge to 20th century regarding to US-Mexican international relations.<br />The collection of another essays "The Other Mexico" focus on Olympics and Tlatelco and the year "1968" which for me as a Czech means significant year in the 20th century.<br />To sum up, this collection of the essays, became classic and belongs to one of the books which should be read in the context of Latin American authors. For me simply, this book means more than for others since I was reading it when have been going througt the most darkest period in my life, with all my feelings and thoughts being with my mum and with my altered ago being with Tutzla people in San Christobal de Las Casas. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4898437382627023270" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
